INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(2,'The Gallery of Lost Art','Tate','The Gallery of Lost Art was an immersive, online exhibition that told the stories of artworks that had disappeared. Curated by Tate, designed by ISO and produced in partnership with Channel 4, with additional support from the The Arts and Humanities Research Council (AHRC), the virtual exhibition explored the sometimes extraordinary and sometimes banal circumstances behind the loss of over forty works of modern and contemporary art by such figures as Marcel Duchamp, Pablo Picasso, Joan Miró, Willem De Kooning, Rachel Whiteread and Tracey Emin.

(http://www.tate.org.uk/about/projects/gallery-lost-art)','http://galleryoflostart.com/','http://galleryoflostart.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Lost_Art_Feature_mac2.jpg','2017-03-12 13:30:48.705725','2017-08-07 05:55:35.810322','http://assets.itsnicethat.com/system/files/072012/4ff1b9e25c3e3c272f00090d/images_slice_large/gallery-of-lost-art-2.jpg?1437411899','Tate Digital champions art and artists by creating rich content experiences to showcase our collection, galleries & exhibitions. We want to make art accessible to everyone.  We balance the needs of visitors who come to the galleries with those who want to learn, participate and engage with art and artists on digital platforms. By providing a compelling online experience Tate will significantly grow its audience and monetise the online traffic.','2012-07-01',200,'This project was interesting in that it specifically chose to use theatrical design to create a visual environment, almost a replication of a physical place, to represent the exhibition space. The contribution of ISO Design Agency allowed the exhibition to take on a fantastical element.

A paper contributed by Jennifer Mundy and Jane Burton of Tate, note that project was started with the recognition that online exhibitions have an enormous, untapped potential for museums and curators to reach a large and genuinely diverse and global audience. They can be visited by anyone anywhere in the world at any time, offering a fantastic platform for the educational mission of museums. In terms of outreach,  they also reach remote and far off visitors who are less inclined to come to museums. They can also offer interesting ways to layer and present information (such as image, text, and interactivity) in the viewing experience. It also notes that digital technology allows viewing objects in high definition with more detail than what is available in galleries. 

Indeed, it was a great success in terms of visitor numbers, but the curators also noted that the exhibition was not taken as seriously by the art press – “a reflection of the difficulty that many in the art world have accepting the intellectual value of sites designed for mass audiences and which are associated in the minds of many with a sphere of popularising communications and transient promotion. This remains a powerful disincentive for further exploration or creative innovation in this field and needs to be addressed, we feel, if the potential of online exhibitions is to be realised and curators, scholars, and artists are to be involved.”

One of the project''s outcomes was to therefore to ask – “Can museums, both large and small, begin to welcome and exploit the opportunities afforded by online exhibitions? Can scholarly curators embrace the medium?”


','2013-01-07','ISO Digital Media, Channel 4','http://galleryoflostart.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/tate_lost928_00005.jpg','https://discardstudies.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/screen-shot-2013-05-01-at-7-03-20-am.png');
INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(3,'Blocked Art','Olga Federova','"Blocked Art" is an online exhibition curated by artist Olga Mikh Federova, featuring images blocked by the government in various countries, displayed in a virtual reality rendered environment.

“I asked my Facebook friends to send me art images which were banned in social media. I created an environment to give a second life to these images. No selection was made.  All images were accepted” said Fedorova, who put the project together.

The online show takes you by the hand, and guides you around the simulated space, moving between ‘rooms’ and artworks that fade in and out through decaying animations and against the backdrop of a glitchy, flittering sound piece. 

The exhibition includes works by Monia Ben Hamouda, Craig Blackmoore, Jakub Ceglarz, Olga Fedorova, Michele Gabriele, Subtle Graces, Maria Jose Alos, Erica Lapadat Janzen, Martina Menegon, Vladimir Mogilevskiy, Sholim Rajovic, Zoe Stawska, Franziska Von Guten, Robert William.','http://www.blockedart.com','http://3752ph102dgl405f3e3yvdrpili.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/gallery/blocked-art-2017-exhibition-photos/OLGA-FEDOROVA-MARTINA-MENEGON-JAKUB-CEGLARZ-MARIA-JOSE-ALOS-SHOLIM-RAJKOVIC-MERT-GUNHAN-VLADIMIR-MOGILEVSKIY.png','2017-03-12 13:45:34.139758','2017-08-05 05:55:26.159237','http://www.aqnb.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/VLADIMIR-MOGILEVSKIY-e1498487939436.png','Olga Fedorova (RUS, 1980, lives and works in Brussels) works in a variety of media such as painting, photograms, sculpture and digital installations. Her work has been shown in a vast array of both physical and online exhibition spaces. Fedorova is an active participant and exhibited artist in different pavilions of The Wrong, the new digital art biennale created in 2013.
','2017-05-22',302,'',NULL,'RAUM (soundtrack)','http://3752ph102dgl405f3e3yvdrpili.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/gallery/blocked-art-2017-exhibition-photos/ERICA-LAPADAT-JANZEN-FRANZISKA-VON-GUTEN.png','http://3752ph102dgl405f3e3yvdrpili.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/gallery/blocked-art-2017-exhibition-photos/OLGA-FEDOROVA.jpg');
INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(6,'The Interface Experience: Forty Years of Personal Computing','Digital Media Lab, Bard Graduate Center',' The Interface Experience offers visitors an opportunity to explore the history of the personal computer and its influence in our lives through unique hands-on experiences. A computer is more than merely an assemblage of plastic, metal, and glass. The Interface Experience presents an opportunity to gain an understanding of how the design of hardware, software, and user interface work in concert to impact our experiences of these machines.

In addition, an innovative staging of the objects and a robust web platform featuring company and product histories, as well as historical print and video advertising for the objects on display (available at www.interface-experience.org) promise to make The Interface Experience simultaneously evocative, interactive, and informative for anyone who has ever used a computer.','http://interface-experience.org/','https://www.bgc.bard.edu/images/InterfaceWebsite.png,660x660','2017-03-12 17:24:45.828855','2017-08-07 06:05:07.732456','https://s.blogcdn.com/slideshows/images/slides/341/693/9/S3416939/slug/l/2014011970-1980-1200jt-1.jpg','Bard Graduate Center is a graduate research institute in New York City. Our Gallery exhibitions and publications, MA and PhD programs, and research initiatives explore
new ways of thinking about decorative arts, design history, and material culture. Founded in 1993, it is an academic unit of Bard College.','2015-04-03',300,'This exhibition interestingly not only takes as its subject matter the history of the experience between device and user, it also incorporates it as part of the means of communication of the ideas in the exhibition.

As a case study into the blending of online-offline resources to create a visitor experience, it uniquely has the computer, the personal technology that has arguably allowed for digital media to exist as it does, as its unabashed centre. The most impressive aspect seems to be, according to many reviews - the seamlessness it achieves. From the connection between the microsite application, audioguide, and the exhibition itself, between the many computers within the exhibition, it most convincingly demonstrates ''interfaces working in concert'' in our everyday lives through how they do so in the exhibition.

Furthermore, the viewer is able to enjoy the unique, evolving experience that is absorbing information from and interacting with devices. To understand the psychology of the experience is key to a lot of the aims of providing unique and impactful aesthetic experiences through digital means.

','2015-07-19','Bard Graduate students','http://chips.nyc/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/interface-experience-m-object-523x900.jpg','http://kimonkeramidas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/IE-2.png');
INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(7,'The Wrong Biennial','David Quiles Guilló','The Wrong is the most compelling digital art biennale today, featuring over 90 curators and 100 artists. Its mission is to create, promote and push positive forward-thinking contemporary digital art to a wider audience worldwide through a biennial event that gathers the best art selected by the best, while embraces the young international talents of today’s exciting digital art scene.

The Wrong is divided into online and IRL locations around the world. The online biennale happens in pavilions; virtual curated spaces in which selected works are exhibited. The offline biennale happens in The Wrong Embassy Network, art spaces, galleries, institutions and artist run spaces in cities around the world which feature temporary AFK projects, featuring live performances, workshops, artist talks and exhibitions.

The first Wrong Biennial was held from November 1st, 2013 to January 31st, 2014
The Wrong Biennial (again) was held from November 1, 2015 to January 31, 2016.
The next Wrong Biennial will take place from November 1st 2017 to January 31st, 2018.','http://thewrong.org/','http://hyperallergic.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/The-Wrong-home.png','2017-03-13 15:32:38.288116','2017-08-07 06:11:30.575777','https://news.artnet.com/app/news-upload/2015/10/the-wrong-3.png','David Quiles Guilló is a cultural producer, curator, artist, and writer. He founded THE WRONG New Digital Art Biennale (since 2013), ABSTRACT EDITIONS (since 2015), a publishing house to deliver Abstract Literature printed to the world, and 7tNbjV (since 2017), a young publishing label focused on releasing abstract literature graphic novels and art projects as paperback print on demand books. In the recent past David founded and managed the festival NOVA Contemporary Culture (2010-2012) and visual art magazine ROJO (2001-2011) among many other projects. ','2013-11-01',2333,'','2018-01-31','The Wrong Council (Yae Akaiwa, Josephine Bosma, Jon Cates, Cürt Clonïnger, Yvette Granata David Quiles Guilló, Florian Kuhlmann, Patrick Lichty, A. Bill Miller,  Kensuke Sembo, Winnie Soon and Miyö Van Stenis.)','https://scontent-nrt1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/19621294_1598698900142374_8308125445748681754_o.png?oh=d6adee90f8ef010e0e86a5db52c02d9b&oe=59F17013','http://www.galeriecharlot.com/media/art1551/Art-galeriecharlot-1890.jpg');
INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(12,'IIIF (International Image Interoperability Framework)','Getty Trust','IIIF (pronounced “triple eye eff”) is the acronym for the International Image Interoperability Framework. This framework comes from a broad community of primarily cultural heritage organizations that are working together to come to practical consensus around the publishing of digital images. By adopting the framework, the public as well as scholars can bring together images from any of the participating organizations for comparison, manipulation, and annotation in a single user interface. This community has agreed upon, published, and implemented two major specifications.','Replicatio variationi servit: “replication serves variation.”','http://d3vjn2zm46gms2.cloudfront.net/blogs/2017/05/31155331/iiif_vangogh_irises.jpg','2017-03-15 18:46:45.961046','2017-08-05 16:53:53.467742','http://d3vjn2zm46gms2.cloudfront.net/blogs/2017/06/01132343/iiif_getty_yale_popes-e1496348937713.png','The J. Paul Getty Trust is an international cultural and philanthropic institution devoted to the visual arts that includes the J. Paul Getty Museum, the Getty Research Institute, the Getty Conservation Institute, and the Getty Foundation. The J. Paul Getty Trust and Getty programs serve a varied audience from two locations: the Getty Center in Los Angeles and the Getty Villa in Pacific Palisades.
 ','2013-08-01',900,'The IIIF, less a display project than a resource for curators and museums to make more efficient their workflow in activities such as organising and curating exhibitions online and offline, or publishing content. 

It exemplifies the way that digital networks can open up use of the archive, effectively establishing a community of institutions that share knowledge and resources from their collections to improve quality and access to art images. 

There are two ways it improves on the usual way visitors are able to view artworks online. The first, is that it notably integrates technologies such as high resolution zoom and an interface for a vast image library.  As an open source API, it also allows cultural institutions to play and experiment with these technologies.

Secondly, it is also invested in creating an online community to ensure the accuracy of annotations, labels, and other information associated with artwork, to safeguard the works'' integrity and representation.',NULL,'Oxford University, the British Library, Stanford University, ARTstor, Die Bayerische Staatsbibliothek (The Bavarian State Library), Cornell University, La Bibliothèque nationale de France (The National Library of France), Nasjonalbiblioteket (The National Library of Norway), Princeton University Library, Wellcome Trust, Yale University (Yale Center for British Art, Beinecke Rare Book & Manuscript Library)','https://iiif.elifesciences.org/journal-cms:content/2016-05/fig1_iiifcolection.jpg/full/full/0/default.jpg','http://showcase.iiif.io/img/showcase/mirador.jpg');
INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(13,'Gallery One','Cleveland Museum of Art','As part of a major 350 million dollar building and renovation project, in which CMA reinstalled and reinterpreted the entire permanent collection in new and renovated gallery spaces, they also decided to undertake a project to explore a couple of questions regarding digital technologies and museums: How can we use interpretive technology to engage visitors actively in new kinds of experiences with works of art? and, What are the best strategies for integrating technology into the project of visitor engagement? 

The Cleveland Museum of Art has responded with the ground-breaking Gallery One, WHICH  draws from extensive audience researc. HThe end result is a highly innovative and robust blend of art, technology, design, and a unique user experience which emerged through the unprecedented collaboration of staff across the museum and with award-winning outside consultants.

','http://www.clevelandart.org/artlens-gallery/original-gallery-one','https://artmuseumteaching.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/lp-cma-collectionswall-01.jpg','2017-03-21 02:38:20.972157','2017-08-07 06:13:05.323695','http://mw2013.museumsandtheweb.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/LP-CMA-FaceArtwork-Child-02.jpg','The Cleveland Museum of Art''s mission is to fulfill its dual roles as one of the world’s most distinguished comprehensive art museums and one of northeastern Ohio’s principal civic and cultural institutions. The museum seeks to augments, preserves, exhibits, and fosters understanding of the outstanding collections of world art it holds in trust for the public and presents complementary exhibitions and programs. The Cleveland Museum of Art embraces its leadership role in collecting, scholarship, education, and community service.','2013-01-21',303,'Gallery One has been an unqualified success for the Cleveland Museum of Art. After opening in 2013, individual attendance at the museum increased by 31% and the attendance of families increased by 29%.','2017-08-07','Local Projects, Zenith Systems, Gallagher & Associates, Piction','http://media.cleveland.com/ent_impact_arts/photo/galleryonejpg-6457c1cb8daf4af9.jpg','http://mw2014.museumsandtheweb.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/GalleryOne_W0H5450.jpg');
INSERT INTO "projects" VALUES(14,'Parallelograms','Rick Silva','Parallelograms is an online artist project exploring the relationship between images and interpretation. Invited artists are given a set of images taken from deliberate web searches and asked to create a web-specific piece in response to one of them. 

By highlighting a wide range of artists, Parallelograms explores a fundamental artistic practice: transforming source material into new forms and ideas. Each project presents a unique way of interpreting an individual image in context of the ubiquitous mass of images found online, and provides insight into the individual artist’s way of working. 

Projects were posted on a regular basis and updates were sent out via a mailing list. The project ended in 2015.','http://www.parallelograms.info/','http://www.leahbeeferman.com/websites/PARALLELOGRAMS1.png','2017-03-25 14:46:03.416626','2017-08-05 16:49:48.886439','http://www.site95.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/ThelanderParallelograms_ManuelFernandez.jpg','Rick Silva is an artist whose recent videos, websites, and images explore notions of landscape and wilderness in the 21st century. He frequently works with the experimental gallery spaces TRANSFER Gallery (NYC) and DITCH PROJECTS (Springfield, OR). Rick lives in Eugene, Oregon, where he also teaches at the University of Oregon.

','2010-10-30',30020,'',NULL,'Leah Beeferman, Matt Harvey','http://mondaysclosed.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Mondaysclosed_009.jpg','http://www.parallelograms.info/35-GW-1.gif');
